post_text: School starts Tuesday, September 8th for students who have completed enrollment or re-enrollment paperwork and have signed out a chrome-book with both a parent and student signature. Without these two requirements in place, students will not be given a schedule. If you still need to complete paperwork and sign out a chrome-book, contact the school immediately! We are closed for the holiday weekend from Friday, September 4 to Monday, September 7. For those with an A.M. seat-time schedule, school begins at 8am. For those with a P.M. seat-time schedule, school begins at 11:55 (if you're eating lunch here). ALL students and visitors must enter through the office doors so we may take your temperature. All departures will be through the doors near the gym. Social distancing requirements will be maintained without debate and ALL students and staff members MUST WEAR A MASK ... this is STATE law.

post_text:
Graduation is scheduled for Tuesday, June 23rd at 7pm.
Here is a breakdown of what is required per the Governor's Executive Order:

Outdoor social gatherings (including graduations) of up to 100 people are permitted with proper six-foot social distancing.
Indoor social gatherings are still limited to no more than 10 people.
Students and other community members are permitted on school property. Per legal counsel, students, parents, staff, etc. will only be allowed to enter schools for the purposes of a social gathering after the school year ends.
Example of allowable graduation ceremony: outdoor ceremony (e.g. on the front lawn) with no more than 100 total people (students, parents, guests and staff) in attendance. For example, a small district with a class of 30 graduates limited to 2 guests each and a handful of staff in attendance, potentially with a small camera crew for live streaming or recording.

Please try to limit your guests to two people. More information to come.

post_text:
Graduation
For planning purposes we want to give as much notice as possible for our graduation plans. As of now, the tentative date for our graduation ceremony will be Tuesday, June 23rd at 7:00 p.m. at Calhoun Community High School on the front lawn (765 Upton Ave.) Again, this is a TENTATIVE date that will rely on the Stay at Home order from the Governor slated to lift on May 28th. If the Stay at Home order is extended, we will have to revisit whether or not we are able to have a graduation ceremony together. Plan B would be to postpone our ceremony to August. For more information, call Mr. Allard at 269-720-6407.

Battle Creek Area Learning Center Seeks Board Member

A board seat will expire on June 30th of 2020. Current board members may seek re-appointment. However, if you have a desire to serve on the board of education for BCALC/CCHS, please submit an application (Form BMR-01 can be picked up in the CCHS by appointment). Please also submit a copy of your resume. Applications and resumes will be reviewed and new board appointments will take place at the July, 2020 meeting.

CCHS is monitoring the COVID-19 situation closely with the Calhoun County Public Health Department. At this time there are NO reported cases of COVID-19 in the state of Michigan. To avoid illness it is best to follow these health precautions:
1. Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20
seconds.
2. Avoid touching your mouth, eyes, and nose with unwashed
hands.
3. Cover your cough with a tissue or sleeve.
4. Remain at home if you are sick.

Please visit the following link for more information

https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/specific-groups/guidance-for-schools.html

CCHS worked with the City of Springfield and the Battle Creek Transit to get a bus stop right in front of our new school. There will be a representative from the BCT at our open house on Wednesday, August 28th. Here are the preliminary route times.

Route 5W AM:

Depart BCT island at 6:45 arrives at HS Stop at 6:50 and 7:30 requires passenger to ride entire trip

Depart BCT island at 7:15 arrives at HS Stop at 7:20 and 8:00 requires passenger to ride entire trip

Depart BCT island at 7:45 arrives at HS Stop at 7:50 and 8:30 requires passenger to ride entire trip

Battle Creek Area Learning Center Seeks Board Members

Two board seats will expire on June 30th of 2019. Current board members may seek re-appointment. However, if you have a desire to serve on the board of education for BCALC/CCHS, please submit an application (Form BMR-01 can be picked up at the CCHS at 765 Upton Ave. Springfield, MI 49037). Please also provide a copy of your resume. Applications and resumes will be reviewed and new board appointments will take place July 1, 2019.

post_text:
Saturday
June 29, 2019 Burma Center 765 Upton Avenue
Springfield, MI 49037

Chemical Bank is now bringing access to financial education directly to the communities we serve through our new Mobile Empowerment Center – a bus catered to provide financial services where individuals and families can receive professional counseling to help them on their path to financial wellness.

In conjunction with local agencies, the Mobile Empowerment Center will be visiting communities throughout Michigan, Ohio and Northern Indiana to host one-day financial education outreach events.

We will be offering:
Financial empowerment presentations on budgeting, banking, and more
Helpful information on fraud, identity theft protection, and mortgages
Financial education about Chemical Bank products and services
Assistance with accessing and understanding a credit report
Credit advice and counseling
Professional finance guidance

post_text: She’s right!
shared_text:
Kenzi Richardson recommends Calhoun Community High School.
June 3, 2019 at 1:04 AM ·

I love this place with all of my heart. They truly care about the students and do all that they can to get their students on track to get where they need to be. The lessons they teach you, stick with you forever. Small classes with places for students to go for extra help. They’re there to help you, not look down on you for needing a little extra help, or push into the right direction. I recommend to anyone looking for an alternative learning place.

post_text:
Senior Meeting Recap:
1. If you haven’t taken the Spring MAP test, we’d like you to do so. Please come in to take the test.
2. If you still have credits that need to be earned, you need to understand that unless your credit requirements are fully completed, you cannot walk.
3. While we cannot deny your diploma if you’ve earned it, we can deny you the walking/ceremony for discipline reasons or fines or fees owed. We can refund you for your cap and gown if you are denied walking.
4. Decorating caps … you can do it but they won’t be issued until the rehearsal. The decoration must stay flat on the mortarboard and must be appropriate.
5. Graduation luncheon and practice … Thursday, May 30th … arrive at Lakeview Middle School by 11:30am … lunch first, caps and gowns issued, pictures if you’d like them by Lifetouch, then graduation rehearsal. Students giving speeches need to stay after rehearsal and practice their speeches in front of staff.
6. If you work, I recommend you take the whole day off. If you need us to call your bosses, let us know.
